f:["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"Orderly Network calculates funding rates hourly based on the premium between perpetual and spot prices across its shared order book. The funding mechanism operates consistently across all frontend partners accessing Orderly's infrastructure, ensuring uniform rates regardless of which DEX interface traders use. Settlement occurs automatically every hour, with funding payments flowing between long and short positions based on market conditions. The shared liquidity model often results in more stable funding rates compared to isolated DEX perpetual markets."}]
10:["$","section",null,{"className":"mb-10","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground mt-12 mb-4","style":{"fontFamily":"var(--font-montserrat), sans-serif"},"children":["Why ","LDO","/","USDT","?"]}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"LDO perpetuals exhibit significant funding rate volatility during Ethereum staking narrative cycles and governance events affecting Lido's protocol. The token's strong correlation with ETH staking yields creates predictable funding rate patterns during periods of high staking activity. Orderly's multi-chain accessibility allows arbitrageurs to capitalize on LDO funding discrepancies across different blockchain ecosystems."}]]}]
11:["$","section","0",{"className":"mb-10","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground mt-12 mb-4","style":{"fontFamily":"var(--font-montserrat), sans-serif"},"children":"Historical Funding Rate Patterns"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"LDO funding rates on Orderly Network typically range from -0.01% to 0.05% during normal market conditions, with extreme spikes reaching ±0.15% during major Ethereum upgrade events or Lido governance proposals. The hourly settlement frequency creates more granular arbitrage windows compared to 8-hour cycles on centralized exchanges. Seasonal patterns emerge around Ethereum staking reward distributions and major DeFi protocol updates affecting liquid staking demand. Weekend trading often shows reduced funding rate volatility due to lower institutional participation in DeFi governance tokens."}]]}]
12:["$","section","1",{"className":"mb-10","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground mt-12 mb-4","style":{"fontFamily":"var(--font-montserrat), sans-serif"},"children":"Cross-DEX Arbitrage Opportunities"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"Orderly's shared liquidity model creates arbitrage opportunities when individual frontend DEXes experience isolated demand spikes for LDO perpetuals. Funding rate discrepancies of 0.02-0.08% frequently occur between Orderly and major CEXes during high volatility periods. The platform's NEAR and EVM compatibility allows for efficient cross-chain arbitrage strategies when LDO spot prices diverge across different blockchain ecosystems. Multi-collateral support enables sophisticated arbitrageurs to optimize capital efficiency by using various stablecoins and blue-chip tokens as margin."}]]}]
13:["$","section","2",{"className":"mb-10","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground mt-12 mb-4","style":{"fontFamily":"var(--font-montserrat), sans-serif"},"children":"Risk Management Considerations"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"Orderly's dependence on frontend partners introduces counterparty risks not present in traditional exchanges, particularly regarding withdrawal processing and account management. The complex multi-chain architecture can create settlement delays during network congestion, potentially impacting time-sensitive arbitrage strategies. Smart contract risks are amplified due to the shared infrastructure model, where vulnerabilities could affect multiple DEX frontends simultaneously. Liquidity fragmentation across different frontend interfaces may result in execution slippage higher than displayed order book depth suggests, requiring careful position sizing for funding rate arbitrage strategies."}]]}]
14:["$","$L16",null,{"items":[{"question":"How does Orderly Network's shared liquidity affect LDO funding rates?","answer":"Orderly's shared order book aggregates LDO trading activity from multiple DEX frontends, typically resulting in more stable funding rates compared to isolated markets. The increased liquidity depth reduces extreme funding spikes, though it may also limit arbitrage opportunities during low volatility periods."},{"question":"What are the advantages of hourly funding settlements for LDO arbitrage?","answer":"Hourly settlements on Orderly provide more frequent arbitrage opportunities and faster capital turnover compared to 8-hour cycles. This is particularly beneficial for LDO given its sensitivity to Ethereum staking events, allowing traders to capture short-term funding rate spikes more effectively."},{"question":"How do Orderly's multi-chain capabilities impact LDO perpetual trading?","answer":"Multi-chain support allows arbitrageurs to access LDO perpetuals using assets from different blockchains as collateral, improving capital efficiency. However, cross-chain bridge risks and potential settlement delays during network congestion must be factored into arbitrage strategies."},{"question":"What risks are unique to funding rate arbitrage on Orderly Network?","answer":"Key risks include dependency on frontend partner stability, complex smart contract architecture across multiple chains, and potential liquidity fragmentation. The shared infrastructure model means that technical issues could simultaneously affect multiple access points to the same underlying liquidity."}]}]
